SIMPLE: rondeau
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rondeau
<hw>Ron*deau"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See
<er>Roundel</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>rondo</asp>.]</altsp>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A species of lyric poetry so composed as to contain a
refrain or repetition which recurs according to a fixed law, and a
limited number of rhymes recurring also by rule.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ When the <xex>rondeau</xex> was called the
<xex>rondel</xex> it was mostly written in fourteen octosyllabic lines
of two rhymes, as in the <xex>rondels</xex> of Charles d'Orleans. . . .
In the 17th century the approved form of the <xex>rondeau</xex> was a
structure of thirteen verses with a refrain.</note> <rj><au>Encyc.
Brit.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>See <er>Rondo</er>, 1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rondel</ent>⟦br⟧
